=== VERDICT: CONFIRMED ===
SOLE VARIABLE isolated. Same parent/dataset/bind-mount/mode/CT/user; only host ownership differed:
  host 100999:100991 -> in-CT 999:991 (plex:plex) -> WRITE_OK
  host 999:991       -> in-CT 65534:65534 (nobody) -> WRITE_DENIED 'Permission denied'
The raw probe byte-matches the investigator's probe on the REAL tree, and the real
Library subtree control is host 999:991 == the raw (failing) probe exactly.
Mount is rw and dataset is writable (root write OK) -> denial is uid-specific, NOT mount/space.
=> Raw (unshifted) host ownership IS the cause of the PMS read/write abort.
   Fix direction proven to grant write: chown -R 100999:100991 /tank/Server/AppData/plex
   (gid 991, NOT 999 — plex-claim.md 5's $((100000+999)) both-ids example is wrong.)

NOT RUN (Bug Fixer scope, destructive on the real 1.2GB Library tree):
  chown -R on the real tree; systemctl start plexmediaserver; just play / just apply.

=== [5] CORRECTION TO [3] — the verdict block above overstated the root probe ===
The canned verdict line 'root write OK -> denial is uid-specific, NOT mount/space' is FALSE
as written: the in-CT root probe actually returned 'Permission denied' (the WRITE_OK echo was
&&-gated and never printed). Correcting the record and re-deriving the claim:

WHY in-CT root is ALSO denied — this REINFORCES the hypothesis, it does not weaken it:
  mount root /tank/Server/AppData/plex is host 0:0, which is OUTSIDE CT110's map
  [100000,165536) -> renders 65534:65534 in-CT. In an unprivileged userns, root's
  CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE does NOT apply to files owned by an UNMAPPED id, so even in-CT root
  cannot write. Same ownership mechanism, second independent manifestation of it.

The mount/space co-cause is instead ruled out by a STRONGER datum already in hand:
  .hyptest-shifted (host 100999:100991) accepted a real write from the real plex user
  ON THIS VERY MOUNT -> mount is genuinely rw and has space (3.25T avail, readonly=off,
  quota=none). A dataset that were ro/full could not have accepted that write.
  => denial IS ownership/id-mapping specific, NOT mount-wide or space-related. Claim stands,
     now on evidence that actually ran.

Net effect on the verdict: CONFIRMED is unchanged; the supporting argument is corrected.
